			<article class="post-2260 post type-post status-publish hentry category-dealbook tag-appointments-and-executive-changes tag-banking-and-financial-institutions tag-credit-and-debt tag-mergers-acquisitions-and-divestitures tag-private-equity tag-regulation-and-deregulation-of-industry des-appointments-and-executive-changes des-banking-and-financial-institutions des-credit-and-debt des-mergers-acquisitions-and-divestitures des-private-equity des-regulation-and-deregulation-of-industry news_keywords-appointments-and-executive-changes news_keywords-banking-and-finance news_keywords-debt news_keywords-mergers-and-acquistions news_keywords-private-equity-2 news_keywords-regulation-and-deregulation" id="post-2260">
                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Comcast in Push to Save Deal</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Dealbook                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-04-20T11:20:34+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">April 20, 2015 7:20 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">April 20, 2015 7:20 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/morning-agenda-comcast-in-push-to-save-deal/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Comcast in Push to Save Deal" data-description=" Comcast in Push to Save Deal| As Debt Deadlines Loom, Greece Calls in a Lawyer | China Moves to Stimulate Growth">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>COMCAST IN PUSH TO SAVE DEAL</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The $45 billion merger of Comcast and Time Warner Cable was announced in February 2014. Now this week starts the process that will make or break the deal. On Wednesday, officials from Comcast and Time Warner Cable and their lawyers will meet with antitrust officials from the Justice Department,  <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/comcast-and-time-warner-cable-to-meet-with-doj-to-negotiate-merger-1429410969?mod=WSJ_hp_LEFTWhatsNewsCollection">The Wall Street Journal reports. </a>  <b>The meeting will be the first</b> where potential concessions will be discussed, The Journal says, citing people familiar with the matter. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The initial hurdle appears to be a high one. Staff lawyers at the Justice Department have raised competition concerns about the merger and <b>are leaning toward a recommendation that it be blocked</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/18/business/media/review-of-comcast-deal-is-said-to-raise-concerns.html?ref=dealbook">report Emily Steel and Ben Protess in The New York Times. </a>  A merger of the two largest cable operators in the country would give the combined company just under 30 percent of pay-television subscribers and some 35 to 50 percent of the nationâs broadband Internet service.  Still, it is somewhat routine for staff lawyers to present objections, and senior officials could overrule a recommendation in any case. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Bloomberg News, which first reported the inclination of the staff lawyers,  <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-04-19/comcast-time-warner-said-to-discuss-deal-with-doj-wednesday">says that Wednesdayâs meeting</a>  âmay focus on Comcastâs involvement with the streaming video service <b>Hulu</b>.â  The <a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/comcast-and-time-warner-cable-to-meet-with-doj-to-negotiate-merger-1429410969?mod=WSJ_hp_LEFTWhatsNewsCollection">Journal cautions</a>  that Wednesdayâs meeting could be the first of many and that it is ânot clear whether the companies can offer concessions that will satisfy regulators.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>AS DEBT DEADLINES LOOM, GREECE CALLS IN A LAWYER</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Persistent worries that Greece could default on its huge debts helped put the markets on edge late last week. âIf Greece were to default and drop out of the euro, global markets might be in for a period of strong turbulence,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/18/business/dealbook/stock-markets-fall-around-the-world.html?ref=dealbook "> noted Peter Eavis in The New York Times. </a> And the time to avert a default is starting to run out.  <b>Christine Lagarde</b>, the managing director of the International Monetary Fund, <a href="//www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/ff441808-e69c-11e4-afb7-00144feab7de.html#axzz3XlpSqCt4 ">told The Financial Times</a>  that last week she had warned Yanis Varoufakis, the Greek finance minister, that any honeymoon the new Greek government may have had with its creditors would soon be over. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another meeting at last weekâs semiannual gathering of the I.M.F. and World Bank in Washington may be an important indicator, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/business/international/greece-flashes-warning-signals-about-its-debt.html?hp&#038;action=click&#038;pgtype=Homepage&#038;module=first-column-region&#038;region=top-news&#038;WT.nav=top-news&#038;_r=0 ">writes Landon Thomas Jr. in The New York Times. </a>  <b>Mr. Varoufakis met with Lee C. Buchheit</b>, the dean of international debt lawyers, who helped broker Greeceâs  â¬200 billion debt refinancing in 2012. âThe meeting,â Mr. Thomas writes,  âsuggests Athens might still be holding out hope for a restructuring of its debt burden of 303 billion euros, or $327 billion.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is not known what the two men discussed on Friday. Still, the idea that the Greek government may be exploring a debt restructuring  <b>   âunderscores just how close Greece is to defaulting on its staggering debt, </b> billions of euros of which must be repaid in the coming weeks,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/business/international/greece-flashes-warning-signals-about-its-debt.html?hp&#038;action=click&#038;pgtype=Homepage&#038;module=first-column-region&#038;region=top-news&#038;WT.nav=top-news&#038;_r=0 ">Mr. Thomas writes. </a>  Greeceâs next formal meeting with its creditors is Friday, when eurozone finance ministers gather in Riga, Latvia.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> <b>Morgan Stanley</b> reports first-quarter results.  President Obama meets with <b>Abu Dhabiâs crown prince</b>, Sheik Mohamed bin Zayed Al-Nahyan.   The 119th running of the <b>Boston Marathon</b> gets underway this morning.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>CHINA MOVES TO STIMULATE GROWTH</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> To stimulate its slowing economy, China appears to be trying to pump more money into the economy while at the same time trying to discourage the use of that money for speculative investments,  <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/business/china-frees-up-200-billion-for-lending.html"> writes Neil Gough in The New York Times</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Peopleâs Bank of China on Sunday moved to free up some $200 billion for new lending, by <b>cutting the reserve requirement ratio for banks by 1 percent</b>, to 18.5 percent. It was the second such move since February and the sharpest cut in seven years.   And it aligns China with easing moves by central banks in Europe and Japan. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The action by the Chinese central bank follows curbs put in place by Chinaâs securities regulator on buying stocks on borrowed money, or on margin, amid a powerful market rally.  On Monday, Shanghaiâs main stock index, which has more than doubled over the last 12 months, fell 1.6 percent.  âIn combination, the policies could help direct more of the new lending into productive sectors of the economy, while <b>reducing the chance that the money further fuels the stock market,</b>â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/20/business/china-frees-up-200-billion-for-lending.html"> Mr. Gough writes.</a> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"></p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></div>
